{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b643a9c5-a888-4a9b-8e4f-0fbf46fb7dc5","content":"\n\n## The Problem\n\n.NET MAUI / .NET Android **bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17** via the `android` workload. When your `JAVA_HOME` points to a third-party JDK (Adoptium Temurin), the build picks it up instead of the expected Microsoft distribution, causing failures.\n\n## The Fix\n\n**Option A — Let MAUI use its bundled JDK (recommended):**\n\nUnset `JAVA_HOME` before building:\n\n```bash\nunset JAVA_HOME\ndotnet build -f net8.0-android\n```\n\nTo make it permanent, remove or comment out the `JAVA_HOME` export in your `~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile`.\n\n**Option B — Point `JAVA_HOME` to the Microsoft OpenJDK:**\n\nThe workload installs it here on macOS:\n\n```bash\nexport JAVA_HOME=\"$HOME/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home\"\n```\n\n**Option C — Set it per-project in your `.csproj`:**\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>$(HOME)/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/microsoft-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nIf you still need Temurin for other projects, Option C is cleanest — it scopes the fix to MAUI without affecting your global `JAVA_HOME`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"db3a3ab8-e34b-4e48-a97e-2f485ab20d44","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nThis is a common issue. .NET MAUI / .NET Android (formerly Xamarin.Android) requires a specific version of JDK. Let me think about what the issue likely is:\n\n1. .NET 8+ MAUI ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 distribution and expects to use that by default.\n2. When JAVA_HOME points to a non-Microsoft JDK, the Android SDK build tools can sometimes fail because the build system expects the Microsoft distribution specifically, or there can be path resolution issues on macOS.\n\n\n3. The real culprit is that .NET MAUI bundles Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and auto-installs it via the `android` workload, but when JAVA_HOME is set to a third-party JDK like Adoptium Temurin, the Android build tasks pick up the wrong JDK, causing subtle incompatibilities. The fix is typically to either unset JAVA_HOME entirely so .NET MAUI uses its bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17, or point JAVA_HOME to the correct Microsoft distribution location. The real issue is that .NET MAUI's build system expects the Microsoft OpenJDK from the workload, and when `JAVA_HOME` points to Temurin instead, it can override `<JavaSdkDirectory>` and cause version mismatches or invalid directory errors. I should focus on explaining this conflict clearly rather than listing all the possible error messages.","outputTokens":1188},"id":"66f987d5-9630-4ea5-9187-4014cba07153","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:49:04.257Z","parentId":"e39fcb07-4217-4c7a-97f6-f78acd4fcf41"}
